'''Dalip Singh Rana''' (born 27 August 1972), better known by the [[ring name]] '''The Great Khali,''' is an Indian-American<ref>{{cite web |title=The Great Khali becomes a U.S. citizen: photos |url=https://www.wwe.com/inside/overtheropes/the-great-khali-us-citizen-photos#fid-26236125 |website=WWE |accessdate=25 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], [[Wrestling promoter|promoter]], model, and actor who is best known for his work in [[WWE]]. He is also the first Indian to win the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]] in WWE history.

A professional wrestler since 2000, Rana was most notably associated with [[WWE]] from 2006 to 2014 where he performed under the name of "The Great Khali". Before embarking on his professional wrestling career, he was an officer for the [[Punjab Police (India)|Punjab Police]]. He has appeared in four [[Hollywood]] films, two [[Bollywood]] films and several television shows.

== Early life ==
Rana was born to Jwala Ram and his wife Tandi Devi in a [[Punjabis|Punjabi]] [[Hindu]] family of the [[Dhiraina]] village of [[Himachal Pradesh]]'s [[Sirmaur district]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/buzz/mouthful/reporter-jumps-on-table-great-khali-interview-229.html|title=When a reporter jumped on table to take The Great Khali's interview|publisher=|date=3 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=What's common between Sunny Leone and The Great Khali?|url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/news/ENT-whats-common-between-sunny-leone-and-the-great-khali-4341186-PHO.html?seq=2&mpage=104|accessdate=14 March 2016|work=[[Dainik Bhaskar]] (English edition)|date=7 August 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315004001/http://daily.bhaskar.com/news/ENT-whats-common-between-sunny-leone-and-the-great-khali-4341186-PHO.html?seq=2&mpage=104|archivedate=15 March 2016}}</ref>

Being one of the seven siblings of a poor family, he had to do odd jobs to make ends meet and suffers from [[acromegaly]], which among other effects causes [[gigantism]] and chin protrusion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/star-wrestler-great-khali-tumor-removed-caused-size/story?id=16874060|title=WWE Star Great Khali's Growth-Inducing Tumor Removed|date=29 July 2012|work=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref> When Rana was serving as a security guard in [[Shimla]], he caught the eye of a police officer from the neighbouring State of Punjab that''—''having previously helped several employees of Punjab Police to become international sportspersons''—''got him inducted into the Punjab Police in 1993,<ref name="indiatimes">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2910680.cms|title=Khali still on Punjab police pay rolls|accessdate=15 June 2008|date=30 March 2008|publisher=The Times of India|first1=Rohit|last1=Mullick}}</ref> and (though Rana was reluctant to leave [[Himachal Pradesh]], his brother was also offered a job in the Punjab Police) once he landed in Punjab's [[Jalandhar]], Rana trained in the local gyms to become a wrestler and soon he got selected for specialised wrestling training in the United States.<ref name="Daily News and Analysis">{{cite news|title=8-FT-HIGH DOORS AWAIT 'THE GREAT KHALI' IN NATIVE VILLAGE|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-8-ft-high-doors-await-the-great-khali-in-native-village-1162883|accessdate=14 March 2016|work=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=5 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314131848/http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-8-ft-high-doors-await-the-great-khali-in-native-village-1162883|archivedate=14 March 2016}}</ref>

== Professional wrestling career ==
=== All Pro Wrestling (2000–2001) ===
Under the ring name Giant Singh he first became a professional wrestler for [[All Pro Wrestling]] (APW) in the United States, making his first appearance in October 2000 when teaming with [[Tony Jones (wrestler)|Tony Jones]] against the West Side Playaz.<ref name="SLAM!"/>

=== World Championship Wrestling (2001) ===
When Rana came to San Francisco, he signed a contract with [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) and spent eight months there, until WCW was bought by their rival promotion, World Wrestling Federation (WWF).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/sports/the-great-khali-from-wwe-ring-to-jalandhars-akhada.html|title=The Great Khali: From WWE ring to Jalandhar's akhada|publisher=dailypioneer.com}}</ref>

=== New Japan Pro-Wrestling (2001–2002) ===
As Giant Singh, he received an offer from [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW) by Team 2000 leader, [[Masahiro Chono]], along with another big man, [[Giant Silva]].<ref name="SLAM!"/> They were the tallest tag team in professional wrestling history at an average height of 7 foot 2½ inches and a combined weight of 805 pounds, teaming up for the first time at the [[Tokyo Dome]] in October when labelled as Club 7 by Chono defeated [[Hiroshi Tanahashi]], [[Kenzo Suzuki]], [[Wataru Inoue (wrestler)|Wataru Inoue]] and [[Yutaka Yoshie]] in a [[professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|handicap Match]] when Silva [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinned]] Tanahashi and Inoue at the same time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/newjapan/tokyodome05.html#1001|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070718171901/http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/newjapan/tokyodome05.html#1001|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 July 2007|title=Indicate of Next results|publisher=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=10 February 2008}}</ref> Singh suffered his first loss in a [[professional wrestling tag team match types|tag team match]] at [[Wrestling World 2002]] in January 2002 after [[Hiroyoshi Tenzan]] pinned him with a [[Pin (professional wrestling)#Cradle|cradle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/newjapan/tokyodome05.html#0102|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070718171901/http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/newjapan/tokyodome05.html#0102|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 July 2007|title=Wrestling World 2002 results|publisher=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=10 February 2008}}</ref> Singh suffered another big tag defeat during March, being pinned by [[Manabu Nakanishi]] after a [[suplex#German suplex|German suplex]] pin, though his most critical loss came in August at Tokyo Nippon Budokan, when after a falling out he was pinned by Silva in a [[professional wrestling match types#Singles match|singles match]].<ref name="SLAM!"/>

=== Various promotions (2002–2006) ===
Starting in 2002, he also wrestled in the Mexican promotion [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] (CMLL) and the Japanese promotion [[All Japan Pro Wrestling]] (AJPW) until 2006, when he signed with WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=16564|title=AJPW 2ND WRESTLE-1|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=cagematch.net}}</ref>

=== World Wrestling Entertainment/WWE ===
==== Deep South Wrestling (2006) ====
[[File:Greatkhali.jpg|thumb|upright|The Great Khali in 2006]]
On 2 January 2006, Rana became the first Indian professional wrestler to be signed to a contract by [[WWE|World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE).<ref name="bbc">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/7384920.stm|title=Giant wrestler finds fame in India|accessdate=6 May 2008|date=6 May 2006|author=Ray, Shantanu Guha |publisher=BBC}}</ref> He was assigned to their [[Farm team#Professional wrestling|developmental federation]], [[Deep South Wrestling]],<ref name="SLAM!"/> where he wrestled under his real name.<ref name="OWOW"/>

==== Early feuds (2006–2007) ====
With [[Shawn Daivari|Daivari]] as his [[Manager (professional wrestling)|manager]], the unnamed Singh debuted on WWE television as a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villain]] on 7 April episode of ''SmackDown!'', attacking [[The Undertaker]] and leaving him defenceless during his match with [[Mark Henry]], thus causing a [[Professional wrestling#No contest|no contest]] ruling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/060407.html|title=SmackDown results – 7 April 2006|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> The following week on ''SmackDown!'' he was introduced as The Great Khali and Daivari explained that he finally had a client who would destroy The Undertaker (after [[Muhammad Hassan (wrestler)|Muhammad Hassan]] and Mark Henry had previously failed).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/060414.html|title=SmackDown results – 14 April 2006|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> Khali made his in-ring debut on 21 April episode of ''SmackDown!'', defeating [[Shoichi Funaki|Funaki]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/060421.html|title=SmackDown results – 21 April 2006|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref>

On 12 May episode of ''SmackDown!'', Khali was [[John Layfield|John Bradshaw Layfield]]'s hand-picked opponent against [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Champion]] [[Rey Mysterio]] (Khali had a height advantage of 21 inches and a weight advantage of 250 pounds) and defeated Mysterio in a [[glossary of professional wrestling terms#Squash|squash match]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/060512.html|title=SmackDown results – 12 May 2006|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> In his match against The Undertaker at [[Judgment Day (2006)|Judgment Day]] on 21 May, Khali defeated The Undertaker with a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Kick|kick to the head]] after receiving some illegal help from Daivari.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/judgementday06.html|title=Judgment Day 2006 results|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/judgmentday/history/2006/matches/23848443/results/|title=The Great Khali makes Undertaker rest in peace|date=21 May 2006|author=Williams, Ed III|accessdate=5 January 2008|publisher=WWE}}</ref> Khali continued on a rampage for several weeks, winning handicap matches,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/060616.html|title=SmackDown results – 16 June 2006|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 May 2008}}</ref> beating wrestlers up in a display of power<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/060602.html|title=SmackDown results – 2 June 2006|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 May 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/060609.html|title=SmackDown results – 9 June 2006|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 May 2008}}</ref><ref name="june23">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/060623.html|title=SmackDown results – 23 June 2006|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 May 2008}}</ref> and mocking The Undertaker's signature pin and victory pose.<ref name="june23"/>

Khali then challenged The Undertaker to a [[professional wrestling match types#Punjabi Prison Match|Punjabi Prison match]] at [[The Great American Bash (2006)|The Great American Bash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/060707.html|title=SmackDown results – 7 July 2006|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> However, Khali was not medically cleared to compete in the match and was instead replaced by [[Big Show]], who lost the match despite Khali's interference. After he was medically cleared, Khali was challenged by The Undertaker to a [[professional wrestling match types#Last Man Standing match|Last Man Standing match]] at [[SummerSlam (2006)|SummerSlam]] on 20 August.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/060804.html|title=SmackDown results – 4 August 2006|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> The match was moved to the ''SmackDown!'' just prior to SummerSlam and was won by The Undertaker, thus giving Khali his first definite loss in WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/060818.html|title=SmackDown results – 18 August 2006|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref>

[[File:The Great Khali and Ranjin Singh.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Khali was accompanied by his translator and manager [[Ranjin Singh (wrestling)|Ranjin Singh]]]]
The Great Khali and Daivari were [[WWE draft|moved]] to the [[ECW (WWE brand)|ECW]] [[WWE brand extension|brand]] officially when they made their ECW debuts on 31 October episode of ''[[ECW (WWE)|ECW on Sci Fi]]'', when Daivari defeated "The Reject" [[Shannon Moore]] in a very quick match.<ref name="trick">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/archive/10312006/|title=Tricks and treats|date=31 October 2006|first=Craig|last=Tello|accessdate=6 January 2008|publisher=WWE}}</ref> Afterwards, Moore was manhandled by Khali.<ref name="trick"/> Daivari continued his ECW winning streak over the next several weeks with The Great Khali usually following up the contest with a [[Powerbomb#Chokebomb|chokebomb]] on Daivari's opponent. At [[December to Dismember (2006)|December to Dismember]] on 3 December, Daivari got a victory over [[Tommy Dreamer]] following a [[Pin (professional wrestling)#Roll-up|roll-up]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated presents: 2007 Wrestling almanac & book of facts|work=Wrestling’s historical cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|page=122}}</ref> Dreamer then chased Daivari backstage, but Khali appeared and caught Dreamer, planting him on the steel ramp with a chokebomb.

On 8 January 2007 episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'', [[Jonathan Coachman]] announced that Khali had signed with Raw (without Daivari, who stayed on ECW) and would wrestle [[John Cena]] in the [[main event]], which Khali won by [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualification]] after Cena took a [[folding chair|steel chair]] held by [[Armando Estrada]] and hit Khali with it, though after the match he performed a [[chokeslam]] on Cena and left the ringside area, leaving Cena prone to an attack by [[Umaga (wrestler)|Umaga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/070108.html|title=RAW results – 8 January 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref>

On 19 February episode of ''Raw'', Khali demanded better competition after easily defeating [[The Highlanders (professional wrestling)|The Highlanders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/070219.html|title=RAW results – 19 February 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> Four days later on ''SmackDown!'', Khali interfered in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls Count Anywhere match|Falls Count Anywhere]] [[Money in the Bank ladder match|Money in the Bank]] qualifying match between [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] and [[Booker T (wrestler)|King Booker]] by costing Kane the match,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/070223.html|title=SmackDown results – 23 February 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref> leading to a feud which culminated in a match at [[WrestleMania 23]] which Khali won In his first appearance at [[WrestleMania]] after slamming Kane with the ''[[chokeslam#Two-handed chokeslam|Khali Bomb]]'' and choking him with a hook and chain at the end of the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/wrestlemania23.html|title=WrestleMania results – 1 April 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref>

[[File:The Great Khali.jpg|thumb|upright|In 2007, Khali feuded with [[John Cena]] over the [[WWE Championship]], a title which he never won]]
On 30 April episode of ''Raw'', Khali attacked [[Edge (wrestler)|Edge]], [[Randy Orton]] and [[Shawn Michaels]] (all three top contenders to the [[WWE Championship]] at the time) backstage.<ref name="april30">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/070430.html|title=RAW results – 30 April 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> Khali then attacked WWE Champion [[John Cena]] as well, sending a message that he wanted Cena's title.<ref name="april30"/> The next week on ''Raw'', Khali defeated Michaels in a number one contender's match for the WWE Championship at [[Judgment Day (2007)|Judgment Day]].<ref name=Judg7>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2007/05/21/4197038.html|accessdate=27 March 2009|last=Elliot|first=Brian|title=WWE just passes on Judgment Day|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|SLAM Sports!]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/070507.html|title=RAW results – 7 May 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> At the event on 20 May, Khali lost via [[Professional wrestling#Submission|submission]] for the first time when [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Tap out|tapping out]] to Cena's ''[[Professional wrestling holds#STF|STFU]]'', though Khali's foot was under the rope and went unnoticed by the referee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/judgementday07.html|title=Judgement Day results 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> The next night on ''Raw'', Khali expressed his outrage over the outcome via his newly established translator and manager, [[Ranjin Singh (wrestling)|Ranjin Singh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/070521.html|title=RAW results – 21 May 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> At [[One Night Stand (2007)|One Night Stand]] on 3 June, Khali lost to Cena after he was hit with an ''[[Professional wrestling throws#Fireman's carry takeover|FU]]'' off a crane bed, thus marking the first time Khali had been pinned in a singles match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/ecwonenightstand07.html|title=One Night Stand 2007 results|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref>

==== World Heavyweight Champion (2007–2008) ====
On 11 June episode of ''Raw'', as part of the [[2007 WWE draft]], Khali was drafted from Raw to SmackDown as SmackDown's first draft pick.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/070611.html|title=RAW results – 11 June 2007 results|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> In July, Khali began a [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] with [[Dave Bautista|Batista]] and the two were scheduled for a match at [[The Great American Bash (2007)|The Great American Bash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/070706.html|title=SmackDown results – 6 July 2007 results|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> However, because Edge [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Vacant|vacated]] the World Heavyweight Championship due to a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Legit|legitimate]] injury, a twenty-man [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|battle royal]] was held for the title on 20 July edition of ''SmackDown!'' which Khali won after eliminating both Kane and Batista in one move, thus winning his first World Heavyweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/070720.html|title=SmackDown results – 20 July 2007 results|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> Khali dominated and defeated both Batista and Kane in a [[professional wrestling match types#basic non-elimination matches|triple threat match]] at The Great American Bash on 22 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/greatamericanbash07.html|title=The Great American Bash 2007 results|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> Khali then debuted a new [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Finisher|finisher]] called the ''Khali Vise Grip'' (a [[Professional wrestling holds#Clawhold|two-handed clawhold]]) which he used to wear down Batista, Kane and [[Ric Flair]].

At [[SummerSlam (2007)|SummerSlam]] on 26 August, Khali lost by disqualification when he used a steel chair, but retained the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/summerslam07.html|title=SummerSlam 2007 results|publisher=Online World of Wrestling.com|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref> Khali then began a feud with Rey Mysterio after Mysterio won a Championship Competition to become the number one contender, leading Khali to apply his ''Visa Grip'' on Mysterio on 7 September episode of ''SmackDown!'' until Batista came to the rescue, with [[List of WWE SmackDown on-air personalities#Authority figures|SmackDown General Manager]] [[Theodore Long]] informing Khali that he would have to defend the World Heavyweight Championship also against Batista in a triple threat match at [[Unforgiven (2007)|Unforgiven]] on 16 September, where Khali's 61-days reign ended after receiving a [[spinebuster]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/unforgiven/matches/|title=Unforgiven 2007 Results|accessdate=16 September 2007|publisher=World Wrestling Entertainment}}</ref> Khali challenged Batista to a rematch in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Punjabi Prison Match|Punjabi Prison match]] at [[No Mercy (2007)|No Mercy]] on 7 October in which Khali lost by failing to escape the Punjabi cage before Batista.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nomercy/matches/52672881/results/|title=No Mercy 2007 results|accessdate=8 October 2007|publisher=World Wrestling Entertainment |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071011001325/http://www.wwe.com/shows/nomercy/matches/52672881/results/|archivedate = 11 October 2007}}</ref>

In late 2007 and early 2008, Khali was put in a program with [[Dave Finlay|Finlay]] usually trying to assault [[Hornswoggle]], but with Finlay stopping him. Khali participated in an [[Elimination Chamber]] match at [[No Way Out (2008)|No Way Out]] on 17 February, which was won by The Undertaker. At [[WrestleMania XXIV]] on 30 March, Khali participated in a twenty-four man battle royal to determine a challenger for [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship|ECW Champion]] Chavo Guerrero later that evening, but the match was won by Kane. Khali then had a short feud with Big Show, culminating in a match at [[Backlash (2008)|Backlash]] on 27 April, which Big Show won.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/backlash/matches/6842782/results/|accessdate=26 July 2008|date=27 April 2008|last=Clayton|first=Corey|title=Big Show wins mammoth matchup|publisher=[[WWE]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080501145517/http://www.wwe.com/shows/backlash/matches/6842782/results/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 1 May 2008}}</ref>

In July, Khali feuded with [[Triple H]] over the WWE Championship and on 25 July episode of ''SmackDown!'' he won a battle royal also involving Big Show, [[Jeff Hardy]], [[Montel Vontavious Porter]], [[Ken Anderson (wrestler)|Mr. Kennedy]] and Umaga to earn the right to face Triple H at [[SummerSlam (2008)|SummerSlam]].<ref name="SD-July-25">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/results/|title=SmackDown: A woman's scorn, a Deadman reborn|date =25 July 2008|accessdate=26 July 2008|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At the event on 17 August, Khali lost to Triple H after receiving a ''[[Facebuster#Double underhook facebuster|Pedigree]]''. Khali was given another opportunity to win the WWE Championship when he faced Jeff Hardy to gain entry into the [[professional wrestling match types#championship scramble|championship scramble]] at [[Unforgiven (2008)|Unforgiven]] on 7 September, but Triple H interfered in the qualification match and aided Hardy with a chair shot to Khali, thus helping Hardy win and eliminating Khali from title contention.

==== Punjabi Playboy (2008–2011) ====
On 3 October, daredevil [[Johnny Knoxville]] aired an interview with Khali and his translator on his website, jackassworld.com, but when Knoxville asked about Khali's "[[penis|taliwacker]]" he became upset and threatened to tip the interview table onto Knoxville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jackassworld.com/blog/2008/10/03/one-bourbon-one-scotch-and-one-beer-%E2%80%93-the-great-khali/|title=One Bourbon, One Scotch, One Beer – Interviewing the Great Khali|accessdate=25 December 2019}}</ref> Khali later invited Knoxville to attend 13 October episode of ''Raw'', where Knoxville was attacked by Khali, [[Women in WWE|WWE Diva]] [[Beth Phoenix]] and Hornswoggle. Khali then took on a more fun persona and became a [[Face (professional wrestling)|fan favourite]] when he and Ranjin Singh hosted the weekly Khali Kiss Cam, where Singh would summon ostensibly random women from the audience to kiss Khali. In May 2009, The Great Khali feuded with [[Dolph Ziggler]], winning by disqualification after Ziggler attacked him with a steel chair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/05/08/9402011.html|title=Smackdown: Hardy's hot, Edge is not|date=8 May 2009|last=McNamara|first=Andy|accessdate=6 January 2010|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> As a result, Khali began coming out to the ring during and after Ziggler's matches, in attempt to gain revenge and to stop Ziggler from cheating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/05/16/9476311.html|title=Smackdown: re-writing a good show|date=16 May 2009|last=Waldman|first=Jon|accessdate=6 January 2010|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=Canadian Online Explorer}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/05/22/9542806.html|title=Smackdown: Edge talks tough, but Hardy delivers|date=22 May 2009|last=McNamara|first=Andy|accessdate=6 January 2010|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> Over the next few weeks, Khali lost to Ziggler by countout and disqualification after Ziggler made it look like Khali hit him with a steel chair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/06/13/9784486.html|title=Smackdown: Contenders and conflict|date=13 June 2009|last=Waldman|first=Jon|accessdate=6 January 2010|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/06/19/9867356.html|title=Smackdown: Jericho outsmarts Mysterio|date=19 June 2009|last=McNamara|first=Andy|accessdate=6 January 2010|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> At [[WWE The Bash|The Bash]] on 28 June, Khali lost to Ziggler by pinfall after Kane returned and attacked Khali.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2009/06/29/9968166.html|title=Mysterio & Jericho save The Bash from wash-out|date=29 June 2009|last=Elliott|first=Brian|accessdate=27 July 2009|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> It was later revealed that Ranjin Singh was Khali's brother, while the feud with Kane resulted in matches at [[SummerSlam (2009)|SummerSlam]] on 23 August and [[WWE Breaking Point|Breaking Point]] on 13 September, both of which Khali lost.<ref name="KhaliKane">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/history/2009/matches/9352646/results/|title=Results:Diabolical destruction|last=Raymond|first=Katie A.|date=23 August 2009|accessdate=23 August 2009|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref><ref>Raymond, Katie A. (23 August 2009) [https://web.archive.org/web/20100410063254/http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/matches/9352646/results/ Results: Diabolical destruction]. ''WWE''.</ref>

Khali required knee surgery and Kane assaulted him with the ring steps during a match so Khali could have time off.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_35358.shtml|title=The Great Khali Keen surgery|publisher=PWTorch|accessdate=4 October 2009}}</ref> Whilst injured, Khali made a surprise appearance alongside Ranjin Singh, [[Ozzy Osbourne]] and his wife [[Sharon Osbourne|Sharon]] on 2 November episode of ''Raw'' as a judge for the Raw's Got Talent segment, in which he hit Chavo Guerrero with a [[professional wrestling attacks#chop|chop]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/11/03/11612636.html|title=RAW: Superstars ride a Crazy Train with Ozzy|date=3 November 2007|last=Plummer|first=Dale|accessdate=2 May 2012|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,14203_5671623,00.html|title=Jerishow punish Cena on RAW|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|accessdate=24 December 2009|date=3 December 2009}}</ref> Khali made his official return on 14 December episode of ''Raw'', teaming with [[Christian Cage|Christian]] and Kane to defeat [[Ezekiel Jackson]], [[Vladimir Kozlov]] and [[William Regal]].

On 2 April episode of ''SmackDown'' it was announced that Khali would take time off to spend time with his family and regroup his thoughts back in India, but he made an appearance as Khaluber (Khali dressed as [[MacGruber]]) on 19 April ''Raw'' by teaming up with special guest host [[Will Forte]] (as MacGruber) in a handicap match against Vladimir Kozlov which they won by intentional countout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local-beat/ashwwe-91586634.html|title=MacGruber to the Rescue for Ash Kicked WWE|publisher=[[WNBC|NBC New York]]|date=20 April 2010|accessdate=10 May 2010|first=James|last=Gardner}}</ref><ref name="NYTimes-0509">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/10/business/media/10wrestle.html|title=Celebrity Guest Hosts Find Fans, and Some Fun, in 'Raw's' Ring|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=9 May 2010|accessdate=10 May 2010|first=Jacques|last=Steinberg}}</ref> As part of the [[2010 WWE draft#Supplemental draft|2010 WWE supplemental draft]], Khali and Ranjin Singh were both drafted back to the Raw brand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2010draft/2010supplementaldraftresults|title=2010 WWE Supplemental Draft results|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=27 April 2010}}</ref> After returning from his hiatus the previous month, Khali was announced by John Cena to be a part of his team along with [[Bret Hart]], [[Chris Jericho]], Edge, [[John Morrison (wrestler)|John Morrison]] and [[Ron Killings|R-Truth]] to face [[The Nexus (Professional wrestling)|The Nexus]] at [[SummerSlam (2010)|SummerSlam]] on 15 August, but on 9 August episode of ''Raw'' he was assaulted and injured by The Nexus, thus removing him from the match. Following the attack, Khali took another hiatus to compete in ''[[Bigg Boss 4|Big Boss]]'', in which he was the runner up on.

Khali made his return at the [[Royal Rumble (2011)|2011 Royal Rumble]], but was eliminated shortly by [[Mason Ryan]]. On 14 March episode of ''Raw'', after Khali defeated [[The Miz]] by disqualification, Miz assaulted Khali with a steel chair, injuring him. Khali won an interbrand [[dark match]] battle royal at [[WrestleMania XXVII]] on 3 April.<ref name="UnitedStates">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemaniaxxvii/over-the-top-rope-battle-royal|title=Results:The Great Khali won the Over-the-Top-Rope WrestleMania Battle Royal|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=5 April 2011}}</ref> On 26 April, Khali was drafted back to SmackDown as part of the [[2011 WWE draft#Supplemental draft|2011 supplemental draft]]. Khali returned on 29 April episode of ''SmackDown'', talking backstage with [[Jinder Mahal]], who made his WWE debut that night. On the 2 May episode of ''Raw'', Khali dressed up as the [[Tooth Fairy (2010 film)|Tooth Fairy]] at [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]]'s birthday party. On the 6 May episode of ''SmackDown'', Mahal''—''unimpressed by how Khali and Ranjin Singh have been partaking in childish activities instead of winning matches''—''confronted Singh about his mismanagement of Khali. Mahal then interrupted a Khali Kiss Cam segment the following week on ''SmackDown'', slapping Khali twice. On the 20 May episode of ''SmackDown'', Mahal interrupted Khali's match against [[The Usos|Jey Uso]], which led to Khali leaving the ring to confront Mahal, who then slapped Khali again, which made Khali re-enter the ring, defeat Jey Uso and then assault [[The Usos|Jimmy Uso]] after the match.

On the 27 May episode of ''SmackDown'', after being defeated by Kane, Mahal came out and shoved Ranjin Singh and then Khali used his ''Vise Grip'' on Singh, thus forming an alliance with Mahal and acting as Mahal's bodyguard, assaulting Mahal's opponent's after his matches. On 1 July edition of ''SmackDown'', Ranjin Singh revealed that Mahal was their [[Kayfabe|brother-in-law]] and that if Khali did not obey Mahal, then he would divorce Khali's sister and put his family back into poverty. On 9 September episode of ''SmackDown'', Khali and Mahal went against [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Champions]] Air Boom ([[Evan Bourne]] and [[Kofi Kingston]]) in a losing effort after Khali pushed Mahal, allowing Kingston to hit his finishing move onto Mahal and after the match he walked away from Mahal, thus endinng their alliance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/2011-05-27/25018171|title=SmackDown results: From dreamer to something meaner|last=Burdick|first=Michael|publisher=[[WWE]]}}</ref> On 23 September episode of ''SmackDown'', Khali defeated Mahal. On 30 September episode of ''SmackDown'', Khali was defeated by World Heavyweight Champion Mark Henry, who after the match "fractured" Khali's fibula with a steel chair.

